<h1>Attorney General Ellison Hails Courtâs Decision to Remove Otto Bremer Trustee as Victory </h1>


<p class="lede">Ramsey County District Court orders removal of Otto Bremer Trustee Brian Lipschultz, terminates self-dealing investment fee, and sets process to appoint successor </p>

<p ><strong>April 29, 2022 (SAINT PAUL)</strong> â Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison today hails the Ramsey County District Court&rsquo;s decision to remove Otto Bremer Trust trustee Brian Lipschultz today as a victory for the charitable beneficiaries of the Otto Bremer Trust.Â Â </p>

<p>Ramsey County District Court Judge Robert Awsumb late today <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2022/docs/OBT_RemovalOrder.pdf" target="_blank">ordered</a> Otto Bremer Trustee Brian Lipschultz&rsquo;s removal in an order that marked the end of an evidentiary hearing into Attorney General Ellison&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2020/08/12_OttoBremerTrust.asp" target="_blank">petition</a> to remove the trustee. This petition came after a months-long <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2020/01/13_OttoBremerTrust.asp" target="_blank">investigation</a> conducted by the Minnesota Attorney General.Â Â Â </p>

<p>Judge Awsumb also ordered the trustees to terminate a self-dealing investment advisory fee that two of the trustees charged the trust, and set forth a process for the parties to confer on the next steps for the appointment of a successor.Â </p>

<p>&ldquo;When I took on the Otto Bremer Trust trustees, I was inspired by my hero and friend, Walter Mondale. In the early 1960s, he released the results of an investigation into Sister Elizabeth Kenny Foundation, a prominent Minnesota charity. When I took on the Otto Bremer Trustees, I knew it would not be easy. But like Mr. Mondale, I took this action because it was the right thing to do,&rdquo; said <strong>Attorney General Ellison</strong>. &ldquo;I am heartened that the Court saw that removing Trustee Lipschultz was the right thing to do for the Trust and its beneficiaries. This is a victory for the integrity of Minnesota&rsquo;s charitable sector and the people of Minnesota.&rdquo;Â </p>

<p>Attorney General Ellison&rsquo;s Office continues to evaluate additional implications of the Court&rsquo;s order, including the Court&rsquo;s decision not to remove the other two Trustees.</p>





	
	
	
